    {"case_name": "Hussainara Khatoon v. State of Bihar", "citation": "AIR 1979 SC 1360", "court": "Supreme Court of India", "year": 1979, "judges": ["P.N. Bhagwati J"], "facts": "A newspaper article revealed that thousands of undertrial prisoners in Bihar were languishing in jails for periods longer than the maximum sentence for the offences they were charged with. A writ petition was filed for their release.", "held": "Right to speedy trial is a fundamental right under Article 21. Undertrial prisoners cannot be kept in jail for periods longer than the maximum sentence for the offence. Courts must ensure speedy justice. The concept of public interest litigation was significantly developed.", "legal_principle": "Speedy trial is an essential component of right to life and liberty under Article 21. Indefinite detention of undertrials is unconstitutional. PIL was recognized as an important tool for constitutional remedy.", "relevant_sections": ["Constitution Article 21", "Constitution Article 22"], "keywords": ["speedy trial", "undertrial prisoners", "bail", "Article 21", "right to liberty", "PIL", "public interest litigation"]},
    {"case_name": "Vishaka v. State of Rajasthan", "citation": "AIR 1997 SC 3011", "court": "Supreme Court of India", "year": 1997, "judges": ["J.S. Verma CJ", "Sujata V. Manohar J", "B.N. Kirpal J"], "facts": "Bhanwari Devi, a social worker, was gang-raped for preventing a child marriage. The case highlighted the absence of legislation protecting women from sexual harassment at the workplace.", "held": "In the absence of legislation, the Supreme Court issued 'Vishaka Guidelines' for protection of women against sexual harassment at the workplace. These guidelines were made legally binding until appropriate legislation was enacted. The POSH Act 2013 later codified these guidelines.", "legal_principle": "Employer has constitutional duty to protect female employees from sexual harassment. In absence of legislation, judicial guidelines are binding under Article 141. The Vishaka Guidelines became the foundation of POSH Act 2013.", "relevant_sections": ["IPC 354", "IPC 376", "Constitution Article 14", "Constitution Article 15", "Constitution Article 21"], "keywords": ["sexual harassment", "workplace harassment", "Vishaka guidelines", "POSH act", "women protection", "fundamental rights"]},
    {"case_name": "State of Maharashtra v. Madhurkar Narayan Mardikar", "citation": "AIR 1991 SC 207", "court": "Supreme Court of India", "year": 1991, "judges": ["K.N. Singh J", "S. Ranganathan J"], "facts": "A police officer was acquitted of charges of rape despite victim's testimony. The sessions court and high court held that the victim was a woman of 'easy virtue' and hence the officer was acquitted.", "held": "Even a woman of easy virtue is entitled to privacy and no one can violate it. Past sexual conduct of a woman cannot be used to discredit her testimony in rape cases. The right to privacy and dignity is inviolable.", "legal_principle": "A woman's past sexual conduct is irrelevant to the question of whether rape occurred. Every woman, regardless of her character or occupation, has a right to dignity and bodily integrity.", "relevant_sections": ["IPC 376", "Indian Evidence Act Section 155(4)"], "keywords": ["rape", "victim character", "sexual assault", "women dignity", "victim blaming", "past conduct irrelevant"]},
    {"case_name": "Arnesh Kumar v. State of Bihar", "citation": "(2014) 8 SCC 273", "court": "Supreme Court of India", "year": 2014, "judges": ["Chandramauli Kumar Prasad J", "Pinaki Chandra Ghose J"], "facts": "The petitioner was sought to be arrested by his wife under IPC Section 498A without proper investigation. The question was whether arrest could be made mechanically in cases under Section 498A.", "held": "Police officers cannot arrest accused automatically in cases under IPC 498A. Magistrates cannot authorize detention mechanically. A check-list of conditions must be satisfied before arrest. The judgment aimed to prevent misuse of Section 498A.", "legal_principle": "Arrest is not automatic; it is last resort. Police and magistrates must apply their minds. Seven categories from Section 41(1)(b) CrPC must be considered. Section 498A should not be weaponized.", "relevant_sections": ["IPC 498A", "CrPC 41", "CrPC 41A"], "keywords": ["arrest", "498A misuse", "dowry harassment", "pre-arrest", "personal liberty", "magistrate authorization"]},
    {"case_name": "Lalita Kumari v. Government of UP", "citation": "(2014) 2 SCC 1", "court": "Supreme Court of India", "year": 2014, "judges": ["P. Sathasivam CJ", "B.S. Chauhan J", "Ranjana Prakash Desai J", "Ranjan Gogoi J", "S.A. Bobde J"], "facts": "Constitutional validity of mandatory registration of FIR under Section 154 CrPC was questioned. Several High Courts had taken different views on whether registration of FIR was mandatory.", "held": "Registration of FIR is mandatory if the information discloses a cognizable offence. Police have no discretion to conduct preliminary inquiry in such cases. However, in cases where prima facie no cognizable offence is made out, preliminary inquiry may be conducted.", "legal_principle": "FIR registration is mandatory for cognizable offences under Section 154 CrPC. Police officer has no discretion to refuse registration. Preliminary inquiry permitted only in limited categories.", "relevant_sections": ["CrPC 154", "CrPC 156"], "keywords": ["FIR", "mandatory registration", "cognizable offence", "police duty", "first information report"]},
    {"case_name": "Sharad Birdhichand Sarda v. State of Maharashtra", "citation": "AIR 1984 SC 1622", "court": "Supreme Court of India", "year": 1984, "judges": ["Fazal Ali J", "A. Varadarajan J"], "facts": "The accused was convicted for murder of his wife based purely on circumstantial evidence. The question was the standard of proof required in cases based on circumstantial evidence.", "held": "The court laid down five golden rules ('Panchasheel') for conviction based on circumstantial evidence: 1. The circumstances from which the conclusion of guilt is to be drawn must be fully established; 2. The facts so established must be consistent only with the hypothesis of guilt; 3. The circumstances must be of a conclusive nature; 4. They must exclude every possible hypothesis except the one to be proved; 5. There must be a chain of evidence so complete as not to leave any reasonable doubt.", "legal_principle": "The Panchasheel test: For conviction on circumstantial evidence, the chain of circumstances must be so complete that it points unerringly to the guilt of the accused and excludes all other reasonable hypotheses.", "relevant_sections": ["IPC 302", "Indian Evidence Act"], "keywords": ["circumstantial evidence", "Panchasheel", "murder proof", "chain of evidence", "reasonable doubt"]},
    {"case_name": "Mohammed Ahmed Khan v. Shah Bano Begum", "citation": "AIR 1985 SC 945", "court": "Supreme Court of India", "year": 1985, "judges": ["Y.V. Chandrachud CJ"], "facts": "Shah Bano, a 73-year-old Muslim woman, was divorced by her husband and sought maintenance under Section 125 CrPC. The question was whether Section 125 CrPC applied to Muslim divorced women.", "held": "Section 125 CrPC is applicable to all women regardless of religion. Muslim divorced women are entitled to maintenance beyond the iddat period if they are unable to maintain themselves. This decision was subsequently overruled by the Muslim Women (Protection of Rights on Divorce) Act, 1986.", "legal_principle": "Section 125 CrPC is a secular provision applicable to all women. Courts have duty to apply uniform law regardless of religion. Rights of women to maintenance transcend religious personal laws.", "relevant_sections": ["CrPC 125", "Muslim Personal Law"], "keywords": ["maintenance", "Muslim divorce", "Shah Bano", "secular law", "CrPC 125", "alimony", "uniform civil code"]},
    {"case_name": "Naz Foundation v. Government of NCT of Delhi", "citation": "(2009) 160 DLT 277", "court": "Delhi High Court", "year": 2009, "judges": ["A.P. Shah CJ", "S. Muralidhar J"], "facts": "The constitutional validity of Section 377 IPC (unnatural offences) was challenged as violating the fundamental rights of LGBT persons. The petition was filed by Naz Foundation, an NGO.", "held": "Section 377 IPC insofar as it criminalizes consensual sexual acts of adults in private, is violative of Articles 14, 15, 19 and 21 of the Constitution. The right to dignity, equality and privacy cannot be denied on the basis of sexual orientation.", "legal_principle": "Sexual orientation is an inherent and immutable part of identity. Consensual private adult acts cannot be criminalized. Constitutional morality must override social morality.", "relevant_sections": ["IPC 377", "Constitution Article 14", "Constitution Article 21"], "keywords": ["Section 377", "LGBT rights", "homosexuality", "decriminalization", "constitutional morality", "privacy rights"]},
    {"case_name": "K.S. Puttaswamy v. Union of India", "citation": "(2017) 10 SCC 1", "court": "Supreme Court of India", "year": 2017, "judges": ["9-Judge Constitution Bench"], "facts": "Constitutional validity of Aadhaar was challenged. Preliminary issue was whether right to privacy is a fundamental right under the Constitution. The government argued that there is no fundamental right to privacy based on earlier judgments.", "held": "Right to Privacy is a fundamental right under Article 21 of the Constitution. The earlier judgments of M.P. Sharma and Kharak Singh (which held to the contrary) were overruled. Privacy includes bodily integrity, personal autonomy, informational privacy, and decisional autonomy.", "legal_principle": "Privacy is a fundamental right. It encompasses informational privacy, bodily integrity, and personal autonomy. State must justify any intrusion into privacy by demonstrating legality, legitimate aim, and proportionality.", "relevant_sections": ["Constitution Article 21", "Constitution Article 14", "Constitution Article 19"], "keywords": ["right to privacy", "Aadhaar", "data protection", "personal liberty", "informational privacy", "fundamental right"]},
